 obtained,\" said Mr. Day, 'and\nstated that despite the high cost of\nbuilding materials they proposed to\nimprove their sites with homes, so as\nto evade the present high rentala which\n1 hcy were paylng.\"\nInterchurch Organization\nWants Others in Building\nReturns 300,000 Square Feel ot*\nBij; Sixth Avenue Building\nlo Market for Rent\nXow that tho Interchurch World\nMovement is fully organized and un?\nder way. all of the former Siegel-Coop\ner-Greenhut department store building,\ncovering the entire east side of Sixth\nAvenue from Eighteenth Street to Nine\ntcenth Street. is not needed by the or\ntranization, and some 300.000 square\nfeet is to be returned to the market.\nAccording to tho Cross Brown\nompany, which has been commis\nsioned to dispose of the space for the\nInterchurch Organization, more than\nS900.000 has been cxpended by the\nowners of the property, in remodeling\nthe structure for use as an office build-\ning. It has been renamed the \"Sixth;\n.V enue Building.\"\nThe Interchurch Movement acquired\nthis property immediately after its\nirbandonment as a base hospital.\nDr. Elbert M. I-'owler of the Inter\nchurch Movement, said yesterday tha'.\ntbe space offered for rent was not I\nmade possible by any desertion from\nthe movement.\n\"We originally leased more space\nthan wo required, that we might be in\na strong position to dictate the charac\nter of the build'.nsi'3 tenancy,\" he\nDwelling Buyers Are\nActive in Bronx Sections\nThe three-story brick dwelling, 10.11 x\nX96.6, at 2407 Walton Avenue has been\nsold by Annie C. Carney to Emma A.\nO'Dea.\nMaud Servoss purchased from Fred?\nerick Mogenheimer 1\"05 Shakcsptare\nAvenue, a two-story dwelling.\nHerman D. Goldbcrg sold to Morris\nWeririan the two-story frame dwelling\nat 2086 Ryer Avenue.\nE. Osborne Smith lnc, sold for Chris\nt.an Wnlaml the dwelling at L'1'50\nGrand Avenue.\nMore \"Manufacturers Quit\nFifth Ave. Shopping District\nMany more manufacturers have\nmoved from the Fifth Avenue retail\n:-hoppinp: zone district in the Savo N'ew\nYork movement. Recent removals of\nmanufacturers outside the district fol?\nlow\nGotthelf Revitz, coats and suits,\n10 East Thirty-third Street, to 38 West\nTwenty-fifth Street; Kohn Brothers,\n'urs, 141 West Thirty-sixth Street, to\n119 West Twenty-mrith Street; Mil- j\nstein Grad. coats and suiu, 63 West\nThirty-sixth Street, to 114 to 120 West,\nrwenty-sixth Street; Gorky Brothers,'\nfurs. 149 Weat Thirty-sixth Street, to i\n145 West Twenty-eignth Street; Colt\nCromVell Company lnc, leather goods,\n149 West Thirty-sixth Street, to R13\nBroadway; Mandelbers: Co., rain-\nvear. 19 West Thirty-fourth Street, to\n46 West Twenty-third Street; J. Ber\nrard Co., furs, 12 East Thirty-tHSrd\nStreet, to 12 and 14 West Twenty\neighth Street; F. Sattij;, costumes, 39:\nWest Thirty-eighth Street. to 13 West\nTwenty-eighth Street; Hoffert Bich\nler, furs, 83 West Thirty-eighth Street,\nto 155 West Twenty-ninth Street; L.\nL. Dress Company, 155 West Thirty\nfourth Street. to 18 West Twenty-sev?\nenth Street. and Peggv Paige, dresses,\n1% West Thirty.fifth Street, t0 18 West\nThirty-second Street.\nCamp Kstate Sells Fordham\nJ{?>inl <>>r. Owned for 50 Yrs.\nThe larg\" vacant plot on the north\n?ide f East Fordham Koad, 100 feet\nr >i of B.-.thgate Avenue. extending\nthrough to East 181st Strct-t, has been\n?old Pease Elliman for the cs?a'e\n<>f Ahigai! amp, which has held title\nfor more than fifty years. lt mcasures\nlQOxlriZx lrregular.\nM. H. Tropauer leased three upper\nff'.ors at 2'Jf> Fifth Avenue to the Prtm\nrose Fashion Producers, lnc\n.1 Arthur Fischer leased to I.ianos\ntt. Banakos a store at the pouthweRt\ncorner of Thirty-ninth Street and Sixth\nAvenue.\n$1,000,000 Brooklyn Home\nCanucci Wolpert purchased for a\ncommunity center improvement a plot\nfronting 154 feet on Church Avenue.\nbetween Flatbush arxi Bedford avenues,\nBrooklyn. P!ar.? ?r?. being prepared\nby George Aspland, architeet, for a\nbuilding thr'\"-